children.name: Console Redirection EMS

children.name: Console Redirection Settings
children.description: The settings specify how the host computer and the remote computer (which the user is using) will exchange data. Both computers should have the same or compatible settings.

children.name: Out-of-Band Mgmt Port
children.description: Microsoft Windows Emergency Management Services (EMS) allows for remote management of a Windows Server OS through a serial port.

children.name: Terminal Type EMS
children.description: VT-UTF8 is the preferred terminal type for out-of-band management. The next best choice is VT100+ and then VT100. See above, in Console Redirection Settings page, for more Help with Terminal Type/Emulation.

children.name: Bits per second EMS
children.description: Selects serial port transmission speed. The speed must be matched on the other side. Long or noisy lines may require lower speeds.

children.name: Flow Control EMS
children.description: Flow control can prevent data loss from buffer overflow. When sending data, if the receiving buffers are full, a 'stop' signal can be sent to stop the data flow. Once the buffers are empty, a 'start' signal can be sent to re-start the flow. Hardware flow control uses two wires to send start/stop signals.

children.name: Redirection COM Port
children.description: Select a COM port to display redirection of Legacy OS and Legacy OPROM Messages

children.name: Resolution
children.description: On Legacy OS, the Number of Rows and Columns supported redirection

children.name: Redirect After POST
children.description: When Bootloader is selected, then Legacy Console Redirection is disabled before booting to legacy OS. When Always Enable is selected, then Legacy Console Redirection is enabled for legacy OS. Default setting for this option is set to Always Enable.

children.name: Remote OS Install
children.description: Enable to Install Legacy OS like Linux in text/graphics mode through redirection When System has Vga. This might not work for all Linux Versions.

children.name: Terminal Type
children.description: Emulation: ANSI: Extended ASCII char set. VT100: ASCII char set. VT100+: Extends VT100 to support color, function keys, etc. VT-UTF8: Uses UTF8 encoding to map Unicode chars onto 1 or more bytes.

children.name: Bits per second
children.description: Selects serial port transmission speed. The speed must be matched on the other side. Long or noisy lines may require lower speeds.

children.name: Data Bits
children.description: Data Bits

children.name: Parity
children.description: A parity bit can be sent with the data bits to detect some transmission errors. Even: parity bit is 0 if the num of 1's in the data bits is even. Odd: parity bit is 0 if num of 1's in the data bits is odd.  Mark: parity bit is always 1. Space: Parity bit is always 0. Mark and Space Parity do not allow for error detection. They can be used as an additional data bit.

children.name: Stop Bits
children.description: Stop bits indicate the end of a serial data packet. (A start bit indicates the beginning). The standard setting is 1 stop bit. Communication with slow devices may require more than 1 stop bit.

children.name: Flow Control
children.description: Flow control can prevent data loss from buffer overflow. When sending data, if the receiving buffers are full, a 'stop' signal can be sent to stop the data flow. Once the buffers are empty, a 'start' signal can be sent to re-start the flow. Hardware flow control uses two wires to send start/stop signals.

children.name: VT-UTF8 Combo Key Support
children.description: Enable VT-UTF8 Combination Key Support for ANSI/VT100 terminals

children.name: Recorder Mode
children.description: With this mode enabled only text will be sent. This is to capture Terminal data.

children.name: Resolution 100x31
children.description: Enables or disables extended terminal resolution

children.name: PERR# Generation
children.description: Enables or Disables PCI Device to Generate PERR#.

children.name: SERR# Generation
children.description: Enables or Disables PCI Device to Generate SERR#.

children.name: Above 4G Decoding
children.description: Enables or Disables 64bit capable Devices to be Decoded in Above 4G Address Space (Only if System Supports 64 bit PCI Decoding).

children.name: SR-IOV Support
children.description: If system has SR-IOV capable PCIe Devices, this option Enables or Disables Single Root IO Virtualization Support.

children.name: BME DMA Mitigation
children.description: Re-enable Bus Master Attribute disabled during Pci enumeration for PCI Bridges after SMM Locked

children.name: Don't Reset VC-TC Mapping
children.description: If system has Vitrtual Channels, Software can reset Traffic Class mapping through Virtual Channels, to it's default state. Setting this option to Enabled will not modify VC Resources.

children.name: PCI Express Settings
children.description: Change PCI Express Devices Settings.

children.name: PCI Express GEN 2 Settings
children.description: Change PCI Express GEN Devices Settings.

children.name: Relaxed Ordering
children.description: Enables or Disables PCI Express Device Relaxed Ordering.

children.name: Extended Tag
children.description: If ENABLED allows Device to use 8-bit Tag field as a requester.

children.name: No Snoop
children.description: Enables or Disables PCI Express Device No Snoop option.

children.name: Maximum Payload
children.description: Set Maximum Payload of PCI Express Device or allow System BIOS to select the value.

children.name: Maximum Read Request
children.description: Set Maximum Read Request Size of PCI Express Device or allow System BIOS to select the value.

children.name: ASPM Support
children.description:
Set the ASPM Level:

Force L0s - Force all links to L0s State

AUTO - BIOS auto configure

DISABLE - Disables ASPM

children.name: Extended Synch
children.description: If ENABLED allows generation of Extended Synchronization patterns.

children.name: Link Training Retry
children.description: Defines number of Retry Attempts software will take to retrain the link if previous training attempt was unsuccessful.

children.name: Link Training Timeout (uS)
children.description: Defines number of Microseconds software will wait before polling 'Link Training' bit in Link Status register. Value range from 10 to 10000 uS.

children.name: Unpopulated Links
children.description: In order to save power, software will disable unpopulated PCI Express links, if this option set to 'Disable Link'.

children.name: Restore PCIE Registers
children.description: On non-PCI Express aware OS's (Pre Windows Vista) some devices may not be correctly reinitialized after S3. Enabling this restors PCI Express device configurations on S3 resume. Warning: Enabling this may cause issues with other hardware after S3 resume.

children.name: Completion Timeout
children.description: In device Functions that support Completion Timeout programmability, allows system software to modify the Completion Timeout value. 'Default' 50us to 50ms. If 'Shorter' is selected, software will use shorter timeout ranges supported by hardware. If 'Longer' is selected, software will use longer timeout ranges.

children.name: ARI Forwarding
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', the Downstream Port disables its traditional Device Number field being 0 enforcement when turning a Type1 Configuration Request into a Type0 Configuration Request, permitting access to Extended Functions in an ARI Device immediately below the Port. Default value: Disabled

children.name: AtomicOp Requester Enable
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this function initiates AtomicOp Requests only if Bus Master Enable bit is in the Command Register Set.

children.name: AtomicOp Egress Blocking
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', outbound AtomicOp Requests via Egress Ports will be blocked.

children.name: IDO Request Enable
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this permits setting the number of ID-Based Ordering (IDO) bit (Attribute[2]) requests to be initiated.

children.name: IDO Completion Enable
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this permits setting the number of ID-Based Ordering (IDO) bit (Attribute[2]) requests to be initiated.

children.name: LTR Mechanism Enable
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this enables the Latency Tolerance Reporting (LTR) Mechanism.

children.name: End-End TLP Prefix Blocking
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this function will block forwarding of TLPs containing End-End TLP Prefixes.

children.name: Target Link Speed
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Force to X.X GT/s' for Downstream Ports, this sets an upper limit on Link operational speed by restricting the values advertised by the Upstream component in its training sequences. When 'Auto' is selected HW initialized data will be used.

children.name: Clock Power Management
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', the device is permitted to use CLKREQ# signal for power management of Link clock in accordance to protocol defined in appropriate form factor specification.

children.name: Compliance SOS
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Enabled', this will force LTSSM to send SKP Ordered Sets between sequences when sending Compliance Pattern or Modified Compliance Pattern.

children.name: Hardware Autonomous Width
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Disabled', this will disable the hardware's ability to change link width except width size reduction for the purpose of correcting unstable link operation.

children.name: Hardware Autonomous Speed
children.description: If supported by hardware and set to 'Disabled', this will disable the hardware's ability to change link speed except speed rate reduction for the purpose of correcting unstable link operation.

children.name: USB Support
children.description: USB Support Parameters

children.name: Legacy USB Support
children.description: Enables Legacy USB support. AUTO option disables legacy support if no USB devices are connected. DISABLE option will keep USB devices available only for EFI applications.

children.name: USB 2.0 Controller Mode
children.description: Configures the USB 2.0 controller in HiSpeed (480Mbps) or FullSpeed (12Mbps).

children.name: XHCI Legacy Support
children.description: Enable/Disable XHCI Controller Legacy support.

children.name: XHCI Hand-off
children.description: This is a workaround for OSes without XHCI hand-off support. The XHCI ownership change should be claimed by XHCI driver.

children.name: EHCI Hand-off
children.description: This is a workaround for OSes without EHCI hand-off support. The EHCI ownership change should be claimed by EHCI driver.

children.name: USB Mass Storage Driver Support
children.description: Enable/Disable USB Mass Storage Driver Support.

children.name: Port 60/64 Emulation
children.description: Enables I/O port 60h/64h emulation support. This should be enabled for the complete USB keyboard legacy support for non-USB aware OSes.

children.name: USB transfer time-out
children.description: The time-out value for Control, Bulk, and Interrupt transfers.

children.name: Device reset time-out
children.description: USB mass storage device Start Unit command time-out.

children.name: Device power-up delay
children.description: Maximum time the device will take before it properly reports itself to the Host Controller. 'Auto' uses default value: for a Root port it is 100 ms, for a Hub port the delay is taken from Hub descriptor.

children.name: Device power-up delay in seconds
children.description: Delay range is 1..40 seconds, in one second increments

children.name: N/A

children.name: IPv4 PXE Support
children.description: Enable/Disable IPv4 PXE boot support. If disabled, IPv4 PXE boot support will not be available.

children.name: IPv4 HTTP Support
children.description: Enable/Disable IPv4 HTTP boot support. If disabled, IPv4 HTTP boot support will not be available.

children.name: IPv6 PXE Support
children.description: Enable/Disable IPv6 PXE boot support. If disabled, IPv6 PXE boot support will not be available.

children.name: IPv6 HTTP Support
children.description: Enable/Disable IPv6 HTTP boot support. If disabled, IPv6 HTTP boot support will not be available.

children.name: PXE LAN Port
children.description: Select PXE LAN port

children.name: PXE boot wait time
children.description: Wait time in seconds to press ESC key to abort the PXE boot. Use either +/- or numeric keys to set the value.

children.name: Media detect count
children.description: Number of times the presence of media will be checked. Use either +/- or numeric keys to set the value.

children.name: CSM Support
children.description: Enable/Disable CSM Support.

children.name: GateA20 Active
children.description: UPON REQUEST - GA20 can be disabled using BIOS services. ALWAYS - do not allow disabling GA20; this option is useful when any RT code is executed above 1MB.

children.name: Option ROM Messages
children.description: Set display mode for Option ROM

children.name: INT19 Trap Response
children.description: BIOS reaction on INT19 trapping by Option ROM: IMMEDIATE - execute the trap right away; POSTPONED - execute the trap during legacy boot.

children.name: Boot option filter
children.description: This option controls Legacy/UEFI ROMs priority

children.name: Network
children.description: Controls the execution of UEFI and Legacy Network OpROM

children.name: PXE LAN Port
children.description: Select PXE LAN port

children.name: Storage
children.description: Controls the execution of UEFI and Legacy Storage OpROM

children.name: Video
children.description: Controls the execution of UEFI and Legacy Video OpROM

children.name: Other PCI devices
children.description: Determines OpROM execution policy for devices other than Network, Storage, or Video

children.name: Secure Boot
children.description: Secure Boot configuration

children.name: Secure Boot
children.description:
Secure Boot feature is Active if Secure Boot is Enabled,

Platform Key(PK) is enrolled and the System is in User mode.

The mode change requires platform reset

children.name: Secure Boot Mode
children.description:
Secure Boot mode options:

Standard or Custom.

In Custom mode, Secure Boot Policy variables can be configured by a physically present user without full authentication

children.name: Restore Factory Keys
children.description:
Force System to User Mode.

Install factory default Secure Boot key databases

children.name: Reset To Setup Mode
children.description: Delete all Secure Boot key databases from NVRAM

children.name: Key Management
children.description:
Enables expert users to modify

Secure Boot Policy variables

without full authentication

children.name: Factory Key Provision
children.description: Install factory default Secure Boot keys after the platform reset and while the System is in Setup mode

children.name: Restore Factory Keys
children.description:
Force System to User Mode.

Install factory default Secure Boot key databases

children.name: Reset To Setup Mode
children.description: Delete all Secure Boot key databases from NVRAM

children.name: Export Secure Boot variables
children.description: Copy NVRAM content of Secure Boot variables to files in a root folder on a file system device

children.name: Enroll Efi Image
children.description:
Allow the image to run in Secure Boot mode.

children.name: Setup Prompt Timeout
children.description: Number of seconds to wait for setup activation key. 65535(0xFFFF) means indefinite waiting.

children.name: Bootup NumLock State
children.description: Select the keyboard NumLock state

children.name: Quiet Boot
children.description: Enables or disables Quiet Boot option

children.name: Boot Option #%d
children.description: Sets the system boot order

children.name: Driver Option #%d
children.description: Sets the system driver order

children.name: Optimized Boot
children.description: Enables or disables Optimized Boot. Enabling Optimized Boot will disable Csm support and disable connecting Network devices to decrease boot time. While disabling Optimized Boot, make sure to restore Csm Support option to previous value before enabling Optimized Boot.

children.name: New Boot Option Policy
children.description: Controls the placement of newly detected UEFI boot options
Set the order of the legacy devices in this group

children.name: Boot Option #%d
children.description: Sets the system boot order

children.name: Save Changes and Exit
children.description: Exit system setup after saving the changes.

children.name: Discard Changes and Exit
children.description: Exit system setup without saving any changes.

children.name: Save Changes and Reset
children.description: Reset the system after saving the changes.

children.name: Discard Changes and Reset
children.description: Reset system setup without saving any changes.

children.name: Save Changes
children.description: Save Changes done so far to any of the setup options.

children.name: Discard Changes
children.description: Discard Changes done so far to any of the setup options.

children.name: Restore Defaults
children.description: Restore/Load Default values for all the setup options.

children.name: Save as User Defaults
children.description: Save the changes done so far as User Defaults.

children.name: Restore User Defaults
children.description: Restore the User Defaults to all the setup options.
